commit.message:
Make builds reproducible

When building the source code, each manpage will use the current date.
This makes builds deterministic. On Debian Systems (and other distros)
this behaviour makes hard generate the same binary (.deb file) between
rebuilds. Please, consider this PR.

Make builds reproducible

When building the source code, each manpage will use the current date.
This makes builds deterministic. On Debian Systems (and other distros)
this behaviour makes hard generate the same binary (.deb file) between
rebuilds. Please, consider this PR.

Add checks for dependencies

bookman command depends of groff and ghostscript. However, the in absence
of these dependencies, no intuitive messages are shown to final users. This
commit adds checks for groff and ghostscript presence and show specific
messages to users.

commit.message:
Print names of manuals to stdout

Print names of manuals to stdout instead of stderr,
because they are often mixed up with gawk's warning messages,
which are also printed out to stderr:

gawk: manual.3cmd. line:58:
warning: regexp escape sequence `\o' is not a known regexp operator

instead of:

gawk: cmd. line:58: warning: regexp escape sequence `\o' is \
      not a known regexp operator
manual.3

commit.message:
Make usage of the date command homogeneous

Signed-off-by: Ismael Luceno <ismael@iodev.co.uk>

Fix usage of the date command on BSD systems

BSD and GNU implementations of the date command are slightly incompatible.

The GNU implementation can take an arbitrary date with the -d option, and
the format is automatically detected, but on BSD implementations it must
be invoked like for setting the system date but using the -j option to
avoid that step, and the input format must be provided with the -f option.

Since the -j option isn't supported by the GNU implementation, it can be
exploited to detect which variant the system uses.

Closes: https://github.com/mvertes/txt2man/issues/19

Signed-off-by: Ismael Luceno <ismael@iodev.co.uk>
